SIMPLE: intromit
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Intromit
<hw>In`tro*mit"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Intromitted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Intromitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>intromittere</ets>,
<ets>intromissum</ets>; <ets>intro-</ets> within + <ets>mittere</ets> to
send.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To send in or put in; to insert or introduce.</def>
<rj><au>Greenhill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To allow to pass in; to admit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Glass in the window <qex>intromits</qex> light, without cold.</q>
<rj><qau>Holder.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intromit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Intromit
<hw>In`tro*mit"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>To
intermeddle with the effects or goods of another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Intromittent</ent>⟦br⟧
